  Clip: {fileID: 8300000, guid: 63041b435517f47688e21373033d5348, type: 3}
  Text: "Samuel Andrews (a fine man), a fervent advocate of Western education, is
    opening a new schoolhouse in the community. As he gathers the local children
    and their parents, he passionately explains the new mo\u2018olelo, emphasizing
    that this modern way of thinking is the only valid approach. He dismisses the
    value of traditional Hawaiian stories and practices, insisting that the students
    must adopt Western attire and grooming standards\u2014short hair, dresses that
    pass the knees, and neatly combed and parted hairstyles.\n\nPerfect.\n\nAs you
    arrive on the scene, you notice a crowd gathered around Andrews, who is fervently
    delivering his speech. You are informed by a concerned parent about the new schoolhouse
    and Andrews\u2019 insistence on erasing traditional Hawaiian culture from the
    curriculum (who needs native history, when we have western magnificence). Realizing
    the gravity of the situation, you step forward to challenge Andrews\u2019 narrow
    perspective. You all argue that while Western education has its merits, traditional
    Hawaiian knowledge and stories hold immense value and should be preserved. What
    is your argument?\n\nSigh."
